      • setNumberTrials

        public void setNumberTrials(int n_trials)
                     throws java.lang.Exception
        Sets the number of Trials used in the stochastic gradient solution. This number should usually be at least 1000 to get reasonable estimates of the source location. Each trial generates a solution be starting a random coordinate inside the bounds of a region where the source is thought to be located. This region is a square box about 200 km outside each coordinate in the navigation list. The default value is 5000.
        Parameters:
        n_trials - Number of trials used in the stochastic gradient solution
        Throws:
        java.lang.Exception - must be greater than 100

      • setAlpha

        public void setAlpha(double alpha)
              throws java.lang.Exception
        Sets the learning rate of the stochastic gradient descent method. This number should usually be between .001 and .0001, and determines the step size in the gradients. For very large geographic areas, a larger step size of .001 should most likely be used. Default value is set at .0001
        Parameters:
        alpha - The step-size in the stochastic gradient descent
        Throws:
        java.lang.Exception - must be a positive number.

      • setNoisePercentage

        public void setNoisePercentage(double noise)
                        throws java.lang.Exception
        Sets the noise percentage used in computing the noisy TDOAs or FDOAs in the simulated multilateration environment. The noise is a number between 0 and 1 (inclusive) that adds a random Gaussian number with standard deviation a percentage of the distance to the given source. Thus the further away from the source, the more noisy the simulated TDOA/FDOA measurement.
        Parameters:
        noise - Percentage of Gaussian noise relative to the distance to source added to the simulated TDOA/FDOA computation
        Throws:
        java.lang.Exception - must be between 0 and 1 (inclusive)

      • setSimulatedNavigationSpeed

                                 throws java.lang.Exception
        Sets the constant speed of the simulated navigation for computing the FDOAs in the simulated multilateration environment. This number should be greater than 0.
        Parameters:
        navigationSpeedMetersPerSec - Speed in meters per second added to the simulated TDOA/FDOA computation
        Throws:
        java.lang.Exception - must be greater than 0

      • filterTDOAfromNavigationList

        public void filterTDOAfromNavigationList(int freq,
                                         double thresh)
                                  throws java.lang.Exception
        Extracts from the filtered navigation list the time-difference on arrival information at each navigation point at the given the frequency channel index. Assumes a frameLength of 65536 milliseconds. It also applies difference filtering where outliers are discarded by taking a difference in time. If the absolute difference is greater than the parameter thresh than the observation is thrown out.
        Parameters:
        freq - Filters on this desired frequency channel
        thresh - Given threshhold on which to throw out outliers
        Throws:
        java.lang.Exception - on filteredNavigationList must not be empty
        See Also:
        NavigationChannelList

      • validateDopplerMeasurement

        public void validateDopplerMeasurement(int freq,
                                       double threshold)
                                throws java.lang.Exception
        Extracts from the filtered navigation list the valid doppler measurements that satisfy the peak list conditions. It modifies the original peak list by dropping all peaks that have a power that is a threshhold smaller than the strongest peak. This rejects correlation peaks artifacts in the time domain that were created by a hard filtering of the transmission channel in the frequency domain. It also only keeps the channels such that the strongest remaining peak is also the first one arriving. This function is used in filterFDOAfromNavigationList
        Parameters:
        freq - Filters on this desired frequency channel index
        threshold - Given threshhold on which to throw out the peaks this much smaller than the strongest
        Throws:
        java.lang.Exception - on filteredNavigationList must not be empty
        See Also:
        NavigationChannelList, filterFDOAfromNavigationList

      • filterFDOAfromNavigationList

        public void filterFDOAfromNavigationList(int freq,
                                         double threshold,
                                         double powerThreshold)
                                  throws java.lang.Exception
        Extracts from the filtered navigation list the valid doppler measurements that satisfy the peak list conditions from validateDopplerMeasurement. It also filters on differences and on observations where the navigation is stationary and yet the fdoa measurment is nonzero. Lastly, all absolute values of fdoa greater that the threshhold parameter are discarded as well.
        Parameters:
        freq - Filters on this desired frequency channel index
        threshold - Given threshhold used to throw out first-order difference outliers
        powerThreshold - threshhold used in the validateDopplerMeasurement
        Throws:
        java.lang.Exception - on filteredNavigationList must not be empty
        See Also:
        NavigationChannelList, validateDopplerMeasurement

      • filterOnRSSI

        public void filterOnRSSI(double threshhold,
                         int freq)
        Filters the navigation list on a specific frequency channel index at a certain threshhold (in dB).

        The measurement will be discarded of the final navigation list if either the frequency index does not exist or if the RSSI measurement is less than the given threshhold.

        Parameters:
        threshhold - the RSSI threshhold. Values less than this will be thrown out of the navigation list
        freq - desired frequency index

      • createEstimationBounds

        public void createEstimationBounds()
                            throws java.lang.Exception
        Once the filtered navigation list has been computed, this function will compute the bounds in which the estimated source might be located. The bounds are found by taking the most extreme north/south/east/west coordinates and adding an additional 200 kilometers in each direction. These bounds are then used in the stochastic gradient method to estimate the source for either the TDOA or FDOA multilateration.
        Throws:
        java.lang.Exception - if matrix dimensions are wrong
        See Also:
        estimateSourceSolutionFDOA, estimateSourceSolutionTDOA

      • estimateSourceSolutionFDOA

        public void estimateSourceSolutionFDOA()
                                throws java.lang.Exception
        Once the navigation log file has been read, and FDOA filtering has been applied using filterFDOAfromNavigationList, this function will estimate the solution using the given FDOAs at the given anchors and computed velocities. The source solution is estimated via means of a stochastic gradient descent approach. All of the given anchors will be used for finding the gradient descent solution The resulting velocities are stored in the navigation list
        Throws:
        java.lang.Exception - flteredNavigationList must be nonempty
        See Also:
        filterFDOAfromNavigationList

      • estimateAdaptiveSourceTDOA

        public void estimateAdaptiveSourceTDOA()
                                throws java.lang.Exception
        Once the navigation log file has been read, and TDOA filtering has been applied using filterTDOAfromNavigationList, this function will estimate the solution using the given anchors and their TDOA estimates in a successive manner. Namely, an estimate of the source will be produced for every successive anchor/tdoa added from the filtered navigation queue. This an estimate will be produced for each additional anchor/tdoa. The solution estimates will be found in a .kml file.
        Throws:
        java.lang.Exception - flteredNavigationList must be nonempty
        See Also:
        filterTDOAfromNavigationList

      • estimateDynamicReferenceTDOA

        public void estimateDynamicReferenceTDOA(int freq,
                                         int n_estimates,
                                         double thresh)
                                  throws java.lang.Exception
        Once the navigation log file has been read, this function will estimate the solution using the given anchors and their TDOA estimates in a successive manner where the first reference anchor changes. Namely, an estimate of the source will be produced for every successive anchor/tdoa added from the filtered navigation queue. The navigation queue will be split up in at most n_estimates separate navigation queues, where the first anchor will be the reference anchor for the TDOA computation. Thus an estimate will be produced for each n_estimate navigation queue. This is to study the effects of the reference location with respect to the source and tdoa computation. The solution estimates will be found in a .kml file called SolutionMarkers_i where i is the i-th segment of the navigation list.
        Parameters:
        freq - The frequency index to use (0,1,2)
        n_estimates - The number of sections the navigation path will be split up into. The reference point for tdoa computation will be the first in the segmented navigation queue.
        thresh - The threshhold used for eliminating outliers in first-order differencing
        Throws:
        java.lang.Exception - flteredNavigationList must be nonempty
        See Also:
        filterTDOAfromNavigationList

      • createNavigationLog

        public void createNavigationLog(java.io.File file)
                         throws java.lang.Exception
        Main function that will parse a navigation log file (*.cir or *.log) into a navigation list that holds all recordings of longitude and latitude in the form of a NavigationChannelList. This Channel list for each coordinate will then give all the frequency index information and store the peak lists for each frequency.

        The output of the function will be a list of NavigationChannelList which can then be filtered on using the different filtering functions

        Parameters:
        file - A navigation file
        Throws:
        java.lang.Exception - if the file is not in the correct format
        See Also:
        NavigationChannelList

      • createSolutionDocument

        public static de.micromata.opengis.kml.v_2_2_0.Kml createSolutionDocument(java.util.ArrayList<double[]> estimates,
                                                                          java.util.ArrayList<java.lang.Double> errors)
        Creates a .kml file to be used in Google Earth that will plot with placemarks all the source estimates and label these source estimates with their respective errors in the given ArrayList. The placemarks will be colored according to their proximity to the source given by the error terms.

      • createNavigationAndSolutionDocument

        public static de.micromata.opengis.kml.v_2_2_0.Kml createNavigationAndSolutionDocument(java.util.ArrayList<double[]> coordinates,
                                                                                       double[] estimate,
                                                                                       int n)
        Creates a .kml file to be used in Google Earth that will plot with placemarks all the source estimates and label these source estimates with their respective errors in the given ArrayList. The placemarks will be colored according to their proximity to the source given by the error terms. These estimates are derived from a segmentation solution, so the segments will be colored as well.
        Parameters:
        coordinates - A collection of anchors node coordinates
        estimate - Their respective estimates
        n - Number [0, number of total segments-1] of the segment being computed
        Returns:
        Kml the handle on the Kml file
